segments.text: I hate this.
You wouldn't think so.
Once daylight came, how much damage had been done to the house?
You'd have to look at the picture.
Our stuff, a lot of it had been carried out and a lot of it hadn't.
First thing I remember was somebody came to me and said, Ms. Williams, your tea set is at such and such a place.
Now, the tea set is in the living room and on the tray it says to Jack Williams from his friends at Clemson.
And the whole tea set was given to him when we left here.
That was carried out.
And then the men started coming in.
You see it was still water dripping and so forth.
And they started carrying things out.
And they were working panically.
They weren't calm at all getting stuff out there.
I don't know where they thought the roof was going to fall in on them or not.
And they were carrying out a chest.
And I said, let me get my clock.
And they didn't even hear me.
And my clock fell and was broken.
I still have it in there patched up.
But people, and I was out in the street.
I went to the bathroom and got his shaving gear and everything we needed and moved it out with us.
And Nelda didn't say anything after she saw that I had gotten it all before we left.
About what percentage of the furnishings, your furnishings, were destroyed?
Half.
No, I would say that not much was completely destroyed.
A lot of it had to be cleaned and reupholstered and that thing.
And the insurance company took care of that.
They were very good about it.
And we moved down to that other house in Bryan.
And what I did was I took the living dining area, they blended together, and I used the living room and dining room as a storage room.
And then I furnished for us the den and a bedroom for us and another bedroom with Jack's office in it.
And of course we had a kitchen, but I just used, I bought a screen that's down in the basement and put it out in the hallway to block off the living room and the dining room.
And that was our storage room for our furniture.
And I can adjust to anything.
If you lived in a trailer without a bathroom for a year and a half, you could certainly live in brine in a house that you knew was temporary.
And one other thing that told you a lot about Jack, we had one man who had helped us when we moved to College Station.
He came in.
I wanted to say Donaldson, that wasn't his name.
Joe Donaldson?
No, that wasn't his name.
Anyway, he came in and started telling me what we needed for the president's house, and he was just out buying it, and then he found out that we were paying for it all.
And when we got our first bill of $3,000, and Jack wrote the bill, wrote the check for it, he found out that the university wasn't buying this stuff that he was bringing in that we needed.
And so he stopped.
He said, I didn't realize you all were paying for this, but I got some nice things out of that $3,000.
And we...
We were okay.
We were going, and I picked the house in, it was picked for me before we got to Houston by the president's wife and the agent showed us his house.
And after we went home, we looked at a few and she called back and said, you want it?
And I said, yes, I want it.
And that was the only one we looked at, the one we lived in on Drummond, close enough to the medical center that Jack could come home for lunch.
Looking back on the A&M years, who would you want to thank most?
for their kindness during those years?
Many names as you want to?
Oh yeah, there'd be a whole lot of names in there.
And they mainly were the people that looked after Jack and looked after things.
And anything I wanted, the university was just wonderful about it.
When I wanted a door just in the family dining room,
to close off the kitchen.
Can you imagine sitting there with somebody at the sink running the dishwasher when you're trying to have a meal in family dining area?
And I asked for a door, and they put me up a beautiful door.
And then when they were enclosing the back, they were going to just cover up enough to broil steaks.
For Earl, they'd had to broil steaks in the rain or something.
So they wanted that enclosed, the idea of
enclosing that area was came from the MSC because they'd had to come over there and work and cater.
And I said, no, let's run it down here.
And we ran it, you know, enlarged it, which was a good addition.
And then after we left, it was enlarged even more.
But I only asked for two things while the time I lived in that Preston's house.
One was that door and the other one was the Amari bowl for the dining room table.
And Bill Paulman, I told Bill Paulman what I wanted.
I wanted a bowl.
Is it still there?
Notice when you go.
I want a bowl that will sit alone.
It needs no flowers that can sit on its own on the middle of this dining room table.
And he said, what do you have in mind?
I said, well, an Amari bowl.
And he came on the airplane and carried it in his hands.
And how much the university paid for that bowl, I don't know.
But Margaret Rutter liked to do flower arrangements.
And I wanted something.
I was growing plants.
I thought green plants brought the house alive.
And so I was just buying them and killing them and buying some more.
Jack didn't care.
You know, it's our money.
But that's the only two things I can remember ever asking for all the time I lived there.
Do you remember any attempts of student humor at the president's house where the students attempted to play a joke or anything or?
do something.
No, only the two times that they rolled the campus, rolled the house.
What were the, was there in a, no, I've seen the picture.
You've seen the one in the bathroom?
Yes.
Okay, that was the second time.
The first time they got caught.
And see, I had the experience of having a teenage daughter in Knoxville, so I knew that if you were attracted to a girl, then you went out and rolled her lawn.
And the first time,
We got now what we did the second time.
Mary said, Mother, all you have to do is get the hose and wash it down.
Mary knew about it.
So anyway, the first time John Coldis came to Jack, they got caught and run off, and they left a whole box of toilet tissue, which I kept.
I couldn't find, say, y'all come back and get your paper.
And the second time, they didn't wake us up, and they've completed the job.
I mean, they really webbed it.
But the first time, John said, don't punish them.
He said, they just said they did it because they liked you.
And the second time is the one we have the picture of in the bathroom.
Have you seen it?
It's in there by the window.
But that was, other than that, the students, can you think of anything they did?
I don't.
No, I can't remember in Aggie lingo any good bull.
Now, didn't they come over to the house one of the first nights y'all were there?
Didn't the band come over and play?
Well, they had a yell session for Jack, and that's when they got the money from the man read about it in the paper.
This is when there was so much problem.
Isn't that sweet, that picture?
Yes, it is.
My brother, my son-in-law, Catherine's husband brought me that from Jerusalem.
He brought me that bowl, and he brought me that vase right there.
When he goes on these trips, he brings me a gift.
All right, we're not far from being finished.
Let me beg you again, please don't, at some point, don't let family papers that relate to experience at Clemson and
Texas A&M, please don't let those get destroyed.
I had said I didn't know what to do, and there's a picture here I want to go back to A&M that's in the living room that Polly Krueger gave us, and I thanked him for it.

I wrote him a letter and thanked him on behalf of the university, and he went to Jack and said, I gave Margaret Rutter one and the other president's wife one, and this is for Margaret, and I want it back if she doesn't want it, and it'll only cost her a kiss.
And so I still have the picture, and he died since then, but I feel like it's not the size.
It means that it should be at the university instead of in either one of the girls' houses.
They could carry it.
Mary said, Mother, I love it.
It's got snow and water both.
You know, she skis with ice and water.
But I would like for that to go back sometime.
And I had said something to Nelda about Jack's papers.
I don't know whether there's anything there that's valuable or not.
There would be for a historian.
But she said, I'll take them.
I'll keep them for you, which is so like her.
Yes.
You know, she had kept clippings for all that time that he was there and had just, we'd moved into the board house, and they were at the foot of his bed on a bench, and the fire water was there.
But she had kept very carefully newspaper clippings for that whole period.

All right, you see, it is to understand the record 10, 50, 100 years from now that I'm concerned about, and the A&M Archives is now in very good condition in the Cushing Library, the old part of the library, and very well organized.
So I'm begging that at some point, whenever you think it's appropriate, perhaps in your estate, that those not be destroyed, but be put at whatever place you think is best, whether it be Clemson or
A&M or Summit both?
Well, I feel like that A&M would be...
I don't think there's much Clemson because Jack had a secretary here that just kept everything.
And every once in a while she would say, I need a new filing cabinet.
So he would send her off to lunch and he would stay there and clear out the filing cabinets.
and say, here's your filing cabinet.
When she got back, he had just emptied enough.
But he threw everything away.
Nelda was the person who kept things.
And a few personal, anything that was controversial here, he did not leave for the next person to have in his files.
He took them to the president and put them in the president's files.
That's good.
That's good.
That's the way he worked.
And whatever he has in there.
Every now and a while I see something.
You know, I've got several things full of papers back there, but I didn't know where to leave them for the girls to try to figure out what to do with them.
We could, Mary and I especially, Mary's the one that's linked to Texas A&M, and Catherine is the brain that has good judgment.
Well, you see, we don't,
People don't keep diaries anymore, and it's these private papers that are the essential.
Well, Jack's diaries were not anything but just a note for himself, what he had to be, where he had to be, and an address or a time.
He didn't write anything else.
And he and I both agreed that it was so sad that here I had kept all his letters for those five years,
that we were, well, three, yeah, five years we knew each other before we married.
And I kept them, and when we moved in this house, I put them in hat boxes in the attic.
And when we were moving to Texas, they had silverfish in them.
So I took them out and took a couple of days to take the garbage can and burn all the letters.
And later...
So that was when he told me everything he did and I knew his friends, I knew these people, and I got a good description.
And we both agreed that it was a sad time, sad that I burned the letters.
And he said, but they were mushy.
You see, that would, like the recent George Bush book of his own, that would be a book right there.
Well, his Marine Corps letters would have been really interesting.
That's what I mean.
But anyway, they were mean.
He and this other man in the Marine Corps, after he ran an office, and every day he wrote he had another job.
They kept adding to his work because he could get it done.
He didn't have any family or anybody.
And he's fast.
But they had this trick that the Navy came in, and see, the Marines have to sleep on the ground, you know, and they don't have any good clean facilities or anything like that.
And the Navy people would come in for billeting.
Jack was the billeting officer and the court recorder and all kinds of things.
And they had a joke about sending them to somebody else.
And they said, no, you get that from so and so.
And they were sending these Navy people all around.
Just out of meanness.
But Jack's next war, he had planned to be in the Navy where you had clean sheets.
What were your feelings about your task at A&M?
What was the president's wife?
What was her role as you thought of it?
Well, my role was I didn't think of myself as being very important now.
My role was to run the house, take care of him, and do whatever somebody told me I should do.
And I added one thing that they still do, the Saul Ross Tee.
That was my idea.
I said, if the ladies come back here and their husbands are in the Sul Ross place, then I should have them for tea.
And I've been reminded since I lived here that they still have the Sul Ross tea.
Have you ever been to a Sul Ross tea?
I used to help you.
Well, I can't remember.
It's all so far back.
But that was my idea.
And then I did do one other thing that was new.
When they got girls sororities, and these were academic sororities, not social, they came for breakfast and initiations.
And I had worked out a system with my caterers that that bar that was out on that back, closed-in area, there's a rolling bar back there.
We could move that up across the kitchen table.
Move it to where it was convenient to the kitchen.
and have a pick-up breakfast on it.
Those groups could come in and have their breakfast and an initiation and be gone in an hour for their 8 o'clock class.
Now that worked out real well.
Of course, the board came unless they wanted to go to see football practice.
We had one board member that was scary.
He would walk out, he would put his cigarette, he never stuffed out a cigarette.
He just put it down, left it burning.
And I would always say, you all go on, I have to do some picking up.
I always stayed to find out how many burning cigarettes he had left around in that wild.

But you know what I'm saying is I didn't feel like when they asked, when the TV station wanted to come out and interview me, I sent back word no because I met her after Jarvis was pressed and I was sitting there with Pinky McCauley and I'd bought tickets for both of us to go to this lunch and they announced that...
But they were glad to have Ms. Williams here as a guest.
And I said out loud, since Pinky was there, I'm not a guest.
I bought two tickets for this.
And I didn't know that the lady across the street with me was the one who had called from the TV station wanting to come out and interview me.
And she identified herself, said, I didn't know who I was eating with.
She didn't know me, and I didn't know her.
And I said, then I explained to her that I said, they have Jack up to their teeth, and they didn't need me, too.
And I did stop the newcomers from going upstairs.
And they wanted to block the steps, and I said, no, that's an insult.
But this is not a house tour.
This is a morning coffee, and they're supposed to visit with people.
And I didn't let them go upstairs.
I don't know whether you remember that or not.
When Dr. Williams was hired, did you assume that they had hired a two-person team?
Never gave it a thought.
We were always, you know, I didn't think about my having a job.
You know, I did what I had to do here, and I wasn't very involved except with his staff at the coordinating board.
And some of the ladies, though, whose husbands were his staff at the board, you know, his media staff, but the members of the board, they came to call on me.
But they lived all over the state, so there wasn't anything much that I could have done about that.
And as I said, that was a time in my life when I was busy raising two girls, and I don't think you'd desert teenage girls.
If someone, next to last question, if someone gave you a million-dollar check now,
and had only one requirement, that you must pass that check on to Texas A&M, but you can decide what the check would be used for.
What would you tell Texas A&M to do with your gift?
This million dollars that somebody hands you and you can pass it on.
Well, it would go back to the former students.
To do what?
Whatever they do.
You'd give them complete free will to use it?
I wouldn't be able to go back there now and say, or to give it to the president.
Jack always sent to Emory & Henry when he made his donations there.
It was always for the president, for his discretionary fund.
And I think you could do that to the president.
He would know where it went.
Now, when somebody dies, when Aggie dies, I send it to the former students.
Mm-hmm.
You know, NELDA keeps me posted and so forth, and that's where I send it, but either to the president for his discretionary budget or to the former students, because I feel like they were
looking after things, and they were so interested in their university.
For instance, now, first thing I'd do would be pay off Joe Moore's debt on the sculpture.
On the sculpture?
I just gave him $500 to start with, but I told him when I was there I'd give him $500 or more again if it didn't already get it off of his back.
And I don't know what in the world it cost him or what it has cost him.
Do you have any idea?
No, I don't.
And who paid for the one that went to Germany?
I have no idea.
They sent me a picture of them gathering in Germany.
They sent me snapshots of that, and that was a beautiful thing to do.
I agree.
All right, what topics have we left out that we should have included?
What have we not talked about that you want to be sure is included in this?
Well, the only thing that I would say was that Jack was blessed with a good staff.
He was blessed with students that were not troublemakers.
A little bit of streaking wasn't a great big deal.
The former students were always there to help.
The faculty wasn't giving them a lot of trouble.
I think things ran rather smoothly.
Now, you would have known where there was a problem here and a problem there.
The dean of women sent one of her problems to Jack.
I told you about that.
You know, everybody has problems in their job, but I think that Jackwood felt like it ran pretty smoothly.
The board wasn't the easiest thing to deal with, but he had good members of the board, wonderful members of the board to help him.
But you have, nothing's perfect, but I have no complaints about anything.
Last question then.
What feelings do you hold in your heart
about Texas A&M now?
I feel like they have a lot of pride in their university, that they're willing to help their university in any way they can.
And there's a lot of ego every place you go, and then a lot of dedicated people that don't ask for any recognition for anything they do.
And...
it was all right for me to go back twice in 20 years let's quit there isn't that okay
